The paper deals with the prophet inequality, which is a classic problem in game theory and mechanism design. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also presents an algorithm for the problem, which involves data structures and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The paper also uses a nontrivial and novel approach, which involves information theory, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the generalization of the results to non-iid distributions, which involves machine learning and artificial intelligence, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the applications of the results in mechanism design, which involves economics and social choice theory, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely sub-category.
